cff-version: 1.2.0
title: >-
  Verifiable AI-Engineered Scientific Software: A GPU-Native
  JAX Reimplementation of a WRF-Compatible Regional Forecast Path
message: >-
  If you use this software or refer to this work, please cite it
  using the metadata below. Authorship: the human author is the
  sole accountable creator of record. AI agents performed roughly
  99.9% of the implementation under the author's direction and are
  credited as non-author contributors (see the `contributors` block
  and the AI-use disclosure in the manuscript, Section 9.5). AI
  systems cannot hold accountability and are therefore not authors.
type: software
authors:
  # Creators (included in the citation). AI systems are NOT listed here:
  # per arXiv/Nature/Zenodo-DataCite practice and the manuscript's own
  # disclosure (Section 9.5), AI cannot be an author/creator because it
  # cannot hold accountability. The human author is the sole creator.
  - given-names: Enric
    family-names: Guenther
    # orcid: 'https://orcid.org/0000-0000-0000-0000'  # PENDING-TAG: add ORCID if available
    # email: enric.r.g@gmail.com                       # PENDING-TAG: confirm public contact at release
abstract: >-
  A governed multi-agent AI system planned, implemented, falsified,
  repaired, and proof-object-validated a GPU-native, JAX/XLA,
  WRF-compatible regional forecast path with the high-frequency model
  state resident on a single consumer GPU (RTX 5090), built on
  subscription-limited model budgets with only roughly-daily human
  steering. The artifact is validated against hard oracles: idealized
  analytic benchmarks (Skamarock warm bubble, Straka density current),
  WRF Fortran operator savepoints, persistence baselines, three real
  72 h Canary Islands 3 km cases scored against same-workstation
  CPU-WRF, conservation and finiteness invariants, a length-independent
  device-residency check, and a roofline-grounded performance study
  (~5.3x clean / ~7.8x realistic over 28-rank CPU-WRF). v0.1.0 is a
  single-domain replay path: it still consumes CPU-WRF/Gen2 boundary
  and land artifacts and lacks live nesting, native initialization, and
  prognostic land surface. The contribution is methodological as much
  as numerical: in a domain with objective oracles, an autonomous AI
  process can build correctness-critical scientific software whose
  trustworthiness — and whose failures — can be checked rather than
  asserted.
keywords:
  - numerical weather prediction
  - WRF
  - GPU
  - JAX
  - XLA
  - regional forecasting
  - scientific software engineering
  - multi-agent AI
  - AI code generation
  - verifiable AI
  - proof-object validation
  - reproducible research
license: AGPL-3.0-or-later
